 "limes-inferior": {
  "bookCover": "https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/6691126-L.jpg",
  "summary": "Limes inferior (Latin for lower limit) is a social science fiction dystopian novel written in 1982 by the Polish author Janusz A. Zajdel. Limes inferior, one of Zajdel's best known works, is a dystopia showing a grim vision of a future society resulting from a merger of the two systems competing at the time - communism and capitalism. It is a seemingly free society, which is in fact tightly controlled through a system of electronic biometric ID cards (Keys), censored media and other forms of social control.\r\n\r\nIt was recognized as the best science fiction novel in Poland in 1982.\r\n\r\ncredit: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limes_inferior",
  "genres": [
   "science-fiction",
   "sci-fi"
  ],
  "tags": [
   "science-fiction",
   "sci-fi"
  ],
  "director": "Janusz A. Zajdel",
  "pages": 284,
  "note": "There is barely anything out there that can make your jaw drop when it comes to foreseeing the future as far ahead and as accurately as Limes Inferior does. While many, especially dystopian titles were meant to do so, this one does in such visceral fashion it's just scary - with descriptions of fictional reality as if an analysis of the contemporary and near-future world written nearly just 4 decades ago.<br/><br/>Even if parts may feel bit off-putting, with the eerie conclusion and relatively slow-burn start, it ultimately became my favorite dystopian novel that can actually be mistaken for reality. The story's progression is impressive with far-reaching descriptions and the ultimate wrap of what it's about."
 },
